{"key":"post-19844803","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>19844803</id>\n<content>There's no need for bad advice.&amp;nbsp; Casing layers should be applied either when the substrate is first made, or right at full colonization when the cover is removed.&amp;nbsp; Never allow contaminants to fall for any period of time on a substrate and then add a casing layer.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I don't want to hear that 'so and so' did it and it was fine.&amp;nbsp; It's bad practice and will fail too often.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;To the OP, you should say 'what' the substrate and proposed casing layer will be.&amp;nbsp; 3&quot; isn't very thick for straw but it's near the point of diminishing returns for manure. Two 2&quot; substrates will produce far more than a single 4&quot; thick substrate.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>19844848</next>\n<prev>19844783</prev>\n<first>19844514</first>\n<last>19849340</last>\n<when>1397518515</when>\n<utime>04/15/14 02:35 AM</utime>\n</post>"}